# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: power-sequencing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] An example of hot swapping is the express ability to pull a Universal Serial Bus (USB) peripheral device, such as a thumb drive, mouse, keyboard, or printer out of a computer's USB slot without powering down the computer first.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Most desktop computer hardware, such as CPUs and memory, are only cold-pluggable.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] However, it is common for mid to high-end servers and mainframes to feature hot-swappable capability for hardware components, such as CPU, memory, PCIe, SATA and SAS drives.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Most smartphones and tablets with tray-loading holders can interchange SIM cards without powering down the system.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Dedicated digital cameras and camcorders usually have readily accessible memory card and battery compartments for quick changing with only minimal interruption of operation.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Batteries can be cycled through by recharging reserve batteries externally while unused.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Many cameras and camcorders feature an internal memory to allow capturing when no memory card is inserted.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Hot swapping is primarily used whenever it is desirable to change the configuration or repair a working system without interrupting its operation.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] A typical example of needing to keep a system running at all times is in the case of a server, a computer that provides access to essential data and applications needed by other computers called clients.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] At other times, hot swapping is implemented simply to avoid the delay and nuisance of shutting down and then restarting a device, such as in the case of charging a smartphone.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Hot swapping is used to add or remove peripherals or components and to replace faulty modules without interrupting equipment operation.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] For example, a machine may have dual hot-swappable power supplies, each adequate enough to power the machine on its own.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] If one of those power supplies breaks and shuts down, the machine will not shut down, as it will draw power from the other, functional power supply.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] The faulty power supply can be replaced during operation of the machine, eventually bringing the machine back to a state of redundancy.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] In the context of servers, important expansion cards, such as disk controllers or host adapters, may be designed with specialized redundancy features in order for these to be replaceable without necessitating interruption of server operation.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Another use case of hot swapping is to enable faster data synchronization between two devices by not having to power down either device before connecting them together.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] For example, plugging an iPhone to a Mac computer via a USB cable to synchronize data between them does not require powering down either the iPhone or the Mac and waiting for them to restart.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] For even more convenience, data synchronization can be configured to start automatically without user input.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] It is also possible to interrupt the data synchronization at any time simply through unplugging the devices, although it's not recommended to do so until instructed to avoid data corruption.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Machines that support hot swapping need to be able to modify their operation for the changed configuration, either automatically on detecting the change, or by user intervention.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] All electrical and mechanical connections associated with hot-swapping must be designed so that neither the equipment nor the user can be harmed while hot-swapping.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Other components in the system must be designed so that the removal of a hot-swappable component does not interrupt operation.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Some implementations require a component shutdown procedure prior to removal.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] This usually results in a simpler design, but such devices are not robust in the case of component failure.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] In such cases, if a component is removed while it is being used, the operations to that device fail and the user is responsible for retrying if necessary.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] In practice, this can be an advantageous trade-off for certain designs where cost matters more than reliability.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] More complex implementations may recommend but do not require that the component be shut down.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] In the suboptimal case a component is removed without being shut down, these implementations usually have sufficient redundancy to allow essential operation to continue.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] In these systems hot swap is normally used for regular maintenance to the computer, or to replace a broken component.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Many devices have functions to eject connected hot-swappable devices to help decrease the chance of data corruption.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] If a device should not be ejected an error message will appear explaining where the device is being used and how to shut it down safely.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Most modern hot-swap methods use a specialized connector with staggered pins, so that certain pins are certain to be connected before others.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Most staggered-pin designs have ground pins longer than the others, ensuring that no sensitive circuitry is connected before there is a reliable system ground.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] The other pins may all be the same length, but in some cases three pin lengths are used so that the incoming device is grounded first, data lines connected second, and power applied third, in rapid succession as the device is inserted.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Pins of the same nominal length do not necessarily make contact at exactly the same time due to mechanical tolerances, and angling of the connector when inserted.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] At one time staggered pins were thought to be an expensive solution, but many contemporary connector families now come with staggered pins as standard; for example, they are used on all modern serial SCSI disk-drives.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Specialized hot-plug power connector pins are now commercially available with repeatable DC current interruption ratings of up to 16 A.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Printed circuit boards are made with staggered edge-fingers for direct hot-plugging into a backplane connector.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Although the speed of plugging cannot be controlled precisely, practical considerations will provide limits that can be used to determine worst-case conditions.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] For a typical staggered pin design where the length difference is 0.5 mm, the elapsed time between long and short pin contact is between 25 ms and 250 ms.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] It is quite practical to design hot-swap circuits that can operate at that speed.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] As long as the hot-swap connector is sufficiently rigid, one of the four corner pins will always be the first to engage.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] For a typical two-row connector arrangement this provides four first-to-make corner pins that are usually used for grounds.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Other pins near the corners can be used for functions that would also benefit from this effect, for example sensing when the connector is fully seated.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] This diagram illustrates good practice where the grounds are in the corners and the power pins are near the center.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Two sense pins are located in opposite corners so that fully seated detection is confirmed only when both of them are in contact with the slot.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] The remaining pins are used for all the other data signals.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] The DC power supplies to a hot-swap component are usually pre-charged by dedicated long pins that make contact before the main power pins.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] These pre-charge pins are protected by a circuit that limits the inrush current to an acceptable value that cannot damage the pins nor disturb the supply voltage to adjacent slots.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] The pre-charge circuit might be a simple series resistor, a negative temperature coefficient (NTC) resistor, or a current-limiter circuit.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Further protection can be provided by a "soft-start" circuit that provides a managed ramp-up of the internal DC supply voltages within the component.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Long (or medium) pre-charge pins make contact; decoupling capacitors start to charge up.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Real time delay of tens of milliseconds.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Soft-start circuit starts to apply power to the component.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Hot-swap power circuits can now be purchased commercially in specially designed ASICs called hot-swap power managers (HSPMs).
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Circuitry attached to signal pins in a hot-swap component should include some protection against electrostatic discharge (ESD).
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] This usually takes the form of clamp diodes to ground and to the DC power supply voltage.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] ESD effects can be reduced by careful design of the mechanical package around the hot-swap component, perhaps by coating it with a thin film of conductive material.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Particular care must be taken when designing systems with bussed signals which are wired to more than one hot-swap component.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] When a hot-swap component is inserted its input and output signal pins will represent a temporary short-circuit to ground.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] This can cause unwanted ground-level pulses on the signals which can disturb the operation of other hot-swap components in the system.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] This was a problem for early parallel SCSI disk-drives.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] One common design solution is to protect bussed signal pins with series diodes or resistors.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] CMOS buffer devices are now available with specialized inputs and outputs that minimize disturbance of bussed signals during the hot-swap operation.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] If all else fails, another solution is to quiesce the operation of all components during the hot-swap operation.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Modern day radio transmitters (and some TV transmitters as well) use high power RF transistor power modules instead of vacuum tubes.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Hot swapping power modules is not a new technology, as many of the radio transmitters manufactured in the 1930s were capable of having power tubes swapped out while the transmitter was running—but this feature was not universally adopted due to the introduction of more reliable high power tubes.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] In the mid-1990s, several radio transmitter manufactures in the US started offering swappable high power RF transistor modules.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] The reintroduction of power modules has been good for the radio transmitter industry, as it has fostered innovation.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Modular transmitters have proven to be more reliable than tube transmitters, when the transmitter is properly chosen for the conditions at the transmitting site.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Although most contemporary video game systems can interchange games and multimedia (e.g.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Blu-rays) without powering down the system, older generations of systems varied in their support of hot-swapping capabilities.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] For example, whereas the Sony PlayStation and PlayStation 2 could eject a game disc with the system powered on, the Nintendo Game Boy Advance and the Nintendo 64 would freeze up and could potentially become corrupt if the game cartridge was removed with the power on.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Manufacturers specifically warned against such practices in the owner's manual or on the game cartridge.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] It was supposedly for this reason that Stop 'N' Swop was taken out of the Banjo-Kazooie series and *Donkey Kong 64*.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] With the Sega Genesis/Mega Drive system, it was sometimes possible to apply cheats (such as a player having infinite lives) and other temporary software alterations to games by hot swapping cartridges, even though the cartridges were not designed to be hot swappable.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Hot-swappable keyboards enable changing the switches without having to disassemble the keyboard.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] On standard mechanical-switch keyboards, the switch is directly soldered to the PCB.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Hot-swappable keyboards instead have a socket in its place that allows the switch to be freely replaced without re-soldering.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Hot-swappable keyboards are becoming increasingly common, and it has become somewhat of a standard in most enthusiast keyboards as well as keyboard components to support hot swapping.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] They can be found in a variety of sizes and layouts, including more specialized ergonomic layouts.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Hot swapping can also refer to the ability to alter the running code of a program without needing to interrupt its execution.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Interactive programming is a programming paradigm that makes extensive use of hot swapping, so the programming activity becomes part of the program flow itself.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Only a few programming languages support hot swapping natively, including Pike, Lisp, Erlang, Smalltalk, Visual Basic 6 (not VB.NET), Java and most recently Elm and Elixir.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Microsoft Visual Studio supports a kind of hot swapping called Edit and Continue, which is supported by C#, VB.NET and C/C++ when running under a debugger.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Hot swapping is the central method in live coding, where programming is an integral part of the runtime process.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] In general, all programming languages used in live coding, such as SuperCollider, TidalCycles, or Extempore support hot swapping.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Some web-based frameworks, such as Django, support detecting module changes and reloading them on the fly.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] However, although the same as hotswapping for most intents and purposes, this is technically just a cache purge, triggered by a new file.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] This does not apply to markup and programming languages such as HTML and PHP respectively, in the general case, as these files are normally reinterpreted on each use by default.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] There are a few CMSes and other PHP-based frameworks (such as Drupal) that employ caching, however.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] In these cases, similar abilities and exceptions apply.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] Hot swapping also facilitates developing systems where large amounts of data are being processed, as in entire genomes in bioinformatics algorithms.
[src:power-sequencing/hot-swapping] The term "HOT PLUG" was registered as a trademark in the United States in November 1992 to Core International, Inc., and cancelled in May 1999.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] A discharged or partially charged capacitor appears as a short circuit to the source when the source voltage is higher than the potential of the capacitor.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] A fully discharged capacitor will take approximately 5 *RC* time periods to fully charge; during the charging period, instantaneous current can exceed steady-state current by a substantial multiple.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Instantaneous current declines to steady-state current as the capacitor reaches full charge.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] In the case of open circuit, the capacitor will be charged to the peak AC voltage (one cannot actually charge a capacitor with AC line power, so this refers to a varying but unidirectional voltage; e.g., the voltage output from a rectifier).
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] In the case of charging a capacitor from a linear DC voltage, like that from a battery, the capacitor will still appear as a short circuit; it will draw current from the source limited only by the internal resistance of the source and ESR of the capacitor.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] In this case, charging current will be continuous and decline exponentially to the load current.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] For open circuit, the capacitor will be charged to the DC voltage.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Safeguarding against the filter capacitor’s charging period’s initial current inrush flow is crucial for the performance of the device.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Temporarily introducing a high resistance between the input power and rectifier can increase the resistance of the powerup, leading to reducing the inrush current.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Using an inrush current limiter for this purpose helps, as it can provide the initial resistance needed.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] When a transformer is first energized, a transient current up to 10 to 15 times larger than the rated transformer current can flow for several cycles.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Toroidal transformers, using less copper for the same power handling, can have up to 60 times inrush to running current.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Unless the windings and core are sized to normally never exceed 50% of saturation (and in an efficient transformer they never are, such a construction would be overly heavy and inefficient), then during such a start-up the core will be saturated.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] This can also be expressed as the remnant magnetism in normal operation is nearly as high as the saturation magnetism at the "knee" of the hysteresis loop.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Once the core saturates, however, the winding inductance appears greatly reduced, and only the resistance of the primary-side windings and the impedance of the power line are limiting the current.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] As saturation occurs for part half-cycles only, harmonic-rich waveforms can be generated and can cause problems to other equipment.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] For large transformers with low winding resistance and high inductance, these inrush currents can last for several seconds until the transient has died away (decay time proportional to *X*L/*R*) and the regular AC equilibrium is established.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] But for toroidal transformers only a premagnetising procedure before switching on allows to start those transformers without any inrush-current peak.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] result of re-energization of transformer.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] The residual flux in this case can be zero or depending on energization timing.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] flow when transformer voltage is restored after having been reduced by system disturbance.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] flow when multiple transformer connected in same line and one of them energized.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] When an electric motor, AC or DC, is first energized, the rotor is not moving, and a current equivalent to the stalled current will flow, reducing as the motor picks up speed and develops a back EMF to oppose the supply.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] AC induction motors behave as transformers with a shorted secondary until the rotor begins to move, while brushed motors present essentially the winding resistance.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] The duration of the starting transient is less if the mechanical load on the motor is relieved until it has picked up speed.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] For high-power motors, the winding configuration may be changed (wye at start and then delta) during start-up to reduce the current drawn.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Metals have a positive temperature coefficient of resistance; they have lower resistance when cold.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Any electrical load that contains a substantial component of metallic resistive heating elements, such as an electric kiln or a bank of tungsten-filament incandescent bulbs, will draw a high current until the metallic element reaches operating temperature.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] For example, wall switches intended to control incandescent lamps will have a "T" rating, indicating that they can safely control circuits with the large inrush currents of incandescent lamps.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] The inrush may be as much as 14 times the steady-state current and may persist for a few milliseconds for smaller lamps up to several seconds for lamps of 500 watts or more.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] (Non-graphitized) carbon-filament lamps, rarely used now, have a negative temperature coefficient and draw more current as they warm up; an "inrush" current is not found with these types.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] A resistor in series with the line can be used to limit the current charging input capacitors.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] However, this approach is not very efficient, especially in high-power devices, since the resistor will have a voltage drop and dissipate some power.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Inrush current can also be reduced by inrush current limiters.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Negative-temperature-coefficient (NTC) thermistors are commonly used in switching power supplies, motor drives and audio equipment to prevent damage caused by inrush current.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] A thermistor is a thermally-sensitive resistor with a resistance that changes significantly and predictably as a result of temperature changes.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] The resistance of an NTC thermistor decreases as its temperature increases.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] As the inrush current limiter self-heats, the current begins to flow through it and warm it.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Its resistance begins to drop, and a relatively small current flow charges the input capacitors.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] After the capacitors in the power supply become charged, the self-heated inrush current limiter offers little resistance in the circuit, with a low voltage drop with respect to the total voltage drop of the circuit.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] A disadvantage is that immediately after the device is switched off, the NTC resistor is still hot and has a low resistance.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] It cannot limit the inrush current unless it cools for more than 1 minute to get a higher resistance.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Another disadvantage is that the NTC thermistor is not short-circuit-proof.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Another way to avoid the transformer inrush current is a "transformer switching relay".
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] It can also deal with power-line half-wave voltage dips and is short-circuit-proof.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] This technique is important for IEC 61000-4-11 tests.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] Another option, particularly for high-voltage circuits, is to use a pre-charge circuit.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] The circuit would support a current-limited precharge mode during the charging of capacitors and then switch to an unlimited mode for normal operation when the voltage on the load is 90% of full charge.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] When a transformer, electric motor, electromagnet, or other inductive load is switched off, the inductor increases the voltage across the switch or breaker and can cause extended arcing.
[src:power-sequencing/inrush-current] When a transformer is switched off on its primary side, inductive kick produces a voltage spike on the secondary that can damage insulation and connected loads.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] A **power management integrated circuit** (**PMIC**) is a multi-function integrated circuit that is used to perform power conversion and control power distribution in an electronic device.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] A PMIC reduces the number of components that would otherwise be necessary for the functions it provides, thus reducing the required circuit board space and improving reliability.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] For example, a PMIC typically includes several DC/DC converters or their control mechanisms.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] PMICs are widely used in computers, battery-powered devices (e.g., mobile phones, tablet computers) and embedded devices.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] Many electronic circuits require multiple power supply voltages (e.g., 5 V, 3.3 V, 1.8 V).
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] PMICs are used to control the delivery of electrical power to such circuits.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] A PMIC integrates various functions related to producing or conveying power supply voltages to external circuitry.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] Typically, the specific functions provided by any particular PMIC are unique to that PMIC model.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] In conjunction with these functions, a PMIC often will perform functions such as voltage supervision and undervoltage lockout.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] Integrating these functions into one IC makes for better conversion efficiency, smaller circuit size, and better heat dissipation.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] A PMIC may include a DC to DC converter to allow dynamic voltage scaling.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] Some models have up to 95% power conversion efficiency.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] Some models integrate with dynamic frequency scaling to support dynamic voltage and frequency scaling (DVFS).
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] Some models can be configured via an I²C or SPI serial communication bus.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] Some models feature a low-dropout regulator (LDO), and a real-time clock (RTC) co-operating with a backup battery.
[src:power-sequencing/power-management-integrated-circuit] A PMIC can use pulse-frequency modulation (PFM) and pulse-width modulation (PWM).
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] A **power-on reset** (**PoR**, **POR**) generator is a microcontroller or microprocessor peripheral that generates a reset signal when power is applied to the device.
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] It ensures that the device starts operating in a known state.
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] In VLSI devices, the **power-on reset** (**PoR**) is an electronic device incorporated into the integrated circuit that detects the power applied to the chip and generates a reset impulse that goes to the entire circuit, placing it into a known state.
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] A simple PoR uses the charging of a capacitor, in series with a resistor, to measure a time period during which the rest of the circuit is held in a reset state.
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] A Schmitt trigger may be used to deassert the reset signal cleanly, once the rising voltage of the RC network passes the threshold voltage of the Schmitt trigger.
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] The resistor and capacitor values should be determined so that the charging of the RC network takes long enough that the supply voltage will have stabilised by the time the threshold is reached.
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] One of the issues with using an RC network to generate a PoR pulse is the sensitivity of the R and C values to the power-supply ramp characteristics.
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] When the power supply ramp is rapid, the R and C values can be calculated so that the time to reach the switching threshold of the Schmitt trigger is enough to apply a long enough reset pulse.
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] When the power-supply ramp itself is slow, the RC network tends to get charged up along with the power-supply ramp up.
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] So when the input Schmitt stage is all powered up and ready, the input voltage from the RC network would already have crossed the Schmitt trigger point.
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] This means that there might not be a reset pulse supplied to the core of the VLSI.
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] On an IBM mainframe, a **power-on reset** (**POR**) is a sequence of actions that the processor performs either due to a POR request from the operator or as part of turning on power.
[src:power-sequencing/power-on-reset] The operator requests a POR for configuration changes that cannot be recognized by a simple System Reset.
